  <content>
    <para id="para-00001">As each functional group is discussed in future chapters, the spectroscopic properties of that group will be described. For the present, we’ll point out some distinguishing features of the hydrocarbon functional groups already studied and briefly preview some other common functional groups. We should also point out, however, that in addition to interpreting absorptions that <emphasis effect="italics">are</emphasis> present in an IR spectrum, it’s also possible to get structural information by noticing which absorptions are <emphasis effect="italics">not</emphasis> present. If the spectrum of a compound has no absorptions at 3300 and 2150 cm<sup>–1</sup>, the compound is not a terminal alkyne; if the spectrum has no absorption near 3400 cm<sup>–1</sup>, the compound is not an alcohol; and so on.</para>
    <section id="sect-00001">
    <title>Alkanes</title>
    <para id="para-00002">The IR spectrum of an alkane is fairly uninformative because no functional groups are present and all absorptions are due to C – H and C – C bonds. Alkane C – H bonds show a strong absorption from 2850 to 2960 cm<sup>–1</sup>, and saturated C –C bonds show a number of bands in the 800 to 1300 cm<sup>–1</sup> range. Since most organic compounds contain saturated alkane-like portions, most organic compounds have these characteristic IR absorptions. The C – H and C – C bands are clearly visible in the three spectra shown previously in <!--<link document="m00141" target-id="fig-00001"/>-->.</para>
    <figure class="unnumbered scaled-down-30" id="fig-00001">
    <media alt="An illustration shows two structures of “alkanes” and their absorption values. The first structure shows a pink carbon having three open bonds on the left; the carbon is pink bonded to a pink hydrogen on the right; the absorption is shown from 2850 - 2960 cm to the power minus one; the second structure shows a pink carbon bonded to another pink carbon; each carbon shows three free bonds; the absorption is shown from 800 - 1300 cm to the power minus one.">
    <image mime-type="image/jpeg" src="../../media/OChem_12_08_001.jpg"/>
    </media>
    </figure>
    </section>
    <section id="sect-00002">
    <title>Alkenes</title>
    <para id="para-00003">Alkenes show several characteristic stretching absorptions. Vinylic =C – H bonds absorb from 3020 to 3100 cm<sup>–1</sup>, and alkene C=C bonds usually absorb near 1650 cm<sup>–1</sup>, although in some cases their peaks can be rather small and difficult to see clearly when the alkene is symmetric, or nearly so. Both absorptions are visible in the 1-hexene spectrum in <!--<link document="m00141" target-id="fig-00001"/>-->b.</para>
    <para id="para-00004">Alkenes have characteristic =C – H out-of-plane bending absorptions in the 700 to 1000 cm<sup>–1</sup> range, thereby allowing the substitution pattern on a double bond to be determined (<link target-id="fig-00003"/>). For example, monosubstituted alkenes such as 1-hexene show strong characteristic bands at 910 and 990 cm<sup>–1</sup>, and 1,1-disubstituted alkenes (R<sub>2</sub>C ═ CH<sub>2</sub>) have an intense band at 890 cm<sup>–1</sup>.</para>
    <figure class="unnumbered scaled-down-30" id="fig-00002">
    <media alt="An illustration shows four structures of alkenes and their absorption values. The first structure shows a double bond attached to a pink carbon bonded to a pink hydrogen; the absorption value shows is 3020-3100 cm to the power minus one. The second structure shows a pink carbon sharing a pink double bond with another pink carbon; each carbon shows two open bonds; the absorption value is 1640 - 1680 cm to the power minus one. The third structure shows R bonded to pink methine sharing a pink double bond with a pink methylene group; the absorption value is 910 and 990 cm to the power minus one. The fourth structure shows R2 bonded to a pink carbon sharing a pink double bond with a pink methylene group; the absorption value is 890 cm to the power minus one.">
    <image mime-type="image/jpeg" src="../../media/OChem_12_08_002.jpg"/>
    </media>
    </figure>
    <figure class="scaled-down" id="fig-00003">
    <media alt="An illustration shows six alkenes and their corresponding bending absorption values. The tabulated format shows two columns comprising of the substituted alkene names and their structural formulas; next follows a scale containing wavelength starting from 10 mu to 15 mu at the interval of 1 mu; the base of the table shows wavenumbers in cm to the power minus one starting from 1000 on the left to 700 on the right; four vertical lines are drawn from top to bottom demarcating the wavenumbers. The bending vibrations are denoted in the form of a blue band. The monosubstituted alkene shows a carbon double bonded to another carbon; the left carbon is bonded to R and hydrogen and the right carbon is bonded to two hydrogens; bands are at 1000 cm to power minus one (10 mu) and 900 cm to the power minus one (11 mu). The cis-1 2 alkene shows a carbon double bonded to another carbon; each carbon is bonded to an R and hydrogen; band is at 740-650 cm to the power minus one (13.5 and 15 mu). The trans-1 2 alkene shows a carbon double bonded to another carbon; the left carbon is bonded to hydrogen at the top and R at the bottom and the right carbon is bonded to R at the top and hydrogen at the bottom; band is at 950 cm to power minus one (10 and 11 mu). The 1 1-disubstituted alkene shows a carbon double bonded to another carbon; the left carbon is bonded to two R and the right carbon is bonded to two hydrogens; band is at 860 to 890 cm to power minus one (11.1 and 11.6 mu). The trisubstituted alkene shows a carbon double bonded to another carbon; the left carbon is bonded to two R and the right carbon is bonded to R and hydrogen; band is at 840 to 780 cm to the power minus one (12 and 13 mu). The tetrasubstituted alkene shows a carbon double bonded to another carbon; each carbon is bonded to four R groups. No band is shown.">
